A UN group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, which has so far been characterized by challenging positions and mutual recriminations, attracted renewed attention on Friday with the dissemination of an ambitious document that foresees reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations carrying most of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time, with over 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Established by a UN ad hoc working group, the text does not discuss how much money the rich countries would give to the poor to face global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what would be the limit of the global increase in the temperature that political strategies would be willing to tolerate.
This gives a lot of flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, high representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's largest climate official, Yvo de Bóer, described as "the great panorama."
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which the industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 from 25 to 45 percent, compared to 1990 levels, while the main developing countries would reduce their emissions during the same period from 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would cut emissions between 50 and 95 percent around 2050.
The European Union also stimulated talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.600 million annually over the next three years, to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
However, Friday was presented the same kind of artificial verbal fires that dominated the talks last week.
The United States Special Climate Envoy, Todd Stern, rejected claims requesting mandatory greenhouse gas emission cuts for industrialized countries, compared with volunteers from major emerging economies, if not funded by the developed world.
The maneuver indicated that the Obama administration is taking a tougher line with China, with respect to what the Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States is not going to make an agreement without major developing countries moving forward and taking action, Stern said, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after the Chinese Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs He Yafei said that the United States' largest climate negotiator lacked "common sense", or was "very irresponsible" for saying earlier in the week that the United States would not help China economically to cope with global warming.
With the future economic trajectory of the world's major powers at stake, the lines of failure have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The present battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the twenty-four countries of the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the strongest action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the major powers are discussing who should cost the costs to limit greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries have become more aggressive seeking to contain the major issuers responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is developing, Ulate supported, who also works as regional advisor on climate change in Mexico and Central America for International Conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the major participants said that talks would ultimately produce a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, with 43 members, prepared a proposal for a preliminary 24-page treaty early on Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said that the push of small island nations has "put political pressure on the whole political process," partly because they are now unified and demand the action of emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks assumed a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that most of the outstanding issues had to be resolved before the heads of government came to an end.
High-level officials, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Deputy Minister, descended from the planes and ran to the Bella Center corridors, to closed meetings and press conferences, in order to be able to define the claims that will be arbitrate during the next week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (where 13,000 people enter and leave the convention centre every day, activists playing the guitar present night shows making fun of the countries they feel are selling themselves, and hand-in-hand preliminary proposals are passed instead of by mail), poses a challenge.
Intensity only builds: almost all key ministers are here right now, and on Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the major leagues," said Carlos Manuel Rodríguez, Vice-President of the Global Policy of International Conservation.
The heavy weights are coming.
