Management revolution or end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with regard to their employees recalls the position of companies with respect to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a matter for the employees to adhere to "values" determined from above as before it was about imposing on consumers products thought by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to the strategies of conquest of the markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are unrelated to the preference factors of customers is repeated regularly.
Demobilization of employees can end up in deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the company's intellectual functions, especially R & D and, even more, business intelligence.
In fact, the BI (Business Intelligence) "requires that all parties involved (...) have proactive conduct and a prospective vision"; it requires employees to make a commitment that fully opposes the recommendations of an authoritarian leadership.
For this reason, we call for a management revolution, which would consist of putting the employees at the centre of the company’s concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion surveys have a relative usefulness
Will internal opinion surveys, such as Orange's questionnaire among its employees, encourage management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many rounds, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did! B989
- Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the diseases of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
-Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from large engineering schools, they interpret psychology mechanically.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the old conductive theory that the U.S. "nerusciences" recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media spread widely behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commands" (sic) of the commitment of the executives, a recent investigation of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms to the managers in a mechanical management position, inadequate to today's world.
Identifying and measuring mobilization factors
On the contrary, the management revolution necessary for the good functioning of modern companies, involves adopting a finalist view of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into all business management reasoning or practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to become a reality of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from the Motifal Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
Studies have shown that they judge their company based on a default dose that enables them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of mobilisation factors, business managers can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate human resource management "in place".
In this way, they create a favourable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
