The dent of the dinosaur
The Tawa found the same look as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal of two meters long and 1.50 meters high that ran on the two strong hind legs, had an extended head with sharp and curved teeth, short arms with blade-shaped claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple million years later, it would not have been something special.
But the Tawa found it was one of the first dinosaurs with these bodily characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of Texas University in Austin and colleagues in the Science magazine on Thursday.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at that time was in a dry area of the Pangea supercontinent in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window towards the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the propagation and characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation in Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes, we have found in one day a dozen dinosaur bones, this is unprecedented for sediments of the Triasic, reports Randall Irmis member of the Utah Natural History Museum team.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation they brought together all the remains of five specimens.
A finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt is an exceptional finding: "Triasic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share such enthusiasm at all.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, for example Martin Sander of Bonn University.
According to current view, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
The experts thus discuss, for example, when the sauries were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous teropods among which the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadruped sauropods known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the Ornithischia herbivores (herbivores with bird pelvis), to which they belong, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to Nesbitt's analysis and his colleagues, Tawa foundae is a primitive teropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in the skull of Tawa find the researchers found signs of airbags, such as those that also own the descendants of the teropods, the birds.
Thanks to air bags, bird breathing is more efficient than mammals.
In the case of Tawa also found the bones of the spine were evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the teropod with older and primitive airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of the later giant sarropods also possessed light-bodies and airbags, it was likely that the common predecessors of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migration waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far known lived in South America, researchers deduced that the saurias appeared there for the first time.
Therefore, the three genealogical lines separated at first and spread from South America across all corners of the Earth, which by then still formed a unique earth mass, the supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say that the team found together with Tawa finds the remains of two other not very closely related thermopods.
The three cannot descend from a single parented predecessor, the researchers argue.
We believe that at least three migration waves were taken to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Of course, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, who belongs to a group of dinosaurs, lived in the present-day Poland, says the paleontologist of Bonn Martin Sander.
Your opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils continue to be preserved, while in other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs evolved from a relatively rare sideline of reptiles to mesozoic dominant terrestrial vertebrates remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in Triasic dinosaurs still shared their vital space with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of current crocodiles and pterosauri and many other saurias.
Toward the end of the Triasic the dinosaurs expanded all over the world and many new species developed, while the kinship extinguished at the limit of the Triasic towards the Jurassic.
Successful Stories Were Not Eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
It may have been given a massive extinction to which dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they could beat the competitors in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact brakes the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triasic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
